abstract: The Republican presidential nominee responded to questions about the Democratic convention, including things said about him there.
snippet: The Republican presidential nominee responded to questions about the Democratic convention, including things said about him there.
lead_paragraph: Donald Trump is mad at me. He thinks I’ve treated him “very badly.” But he returned my call on Friday night on his way to a rally in Colorado and agreed to do a lightning round on the Democratic convention. He began, naturally, by bragging about his convention ratings and bounce, but then we got down to specifics.

abstract: Arthur C. Brooks and Gail Collins chew over Hillary’s speech and the best Republican convention Democrats ever had.
snippet: Arthur C. Brooks and Gail Collins chew over Hillary’s speech and the best Republican convention Democrats ever had.
lead_paragraph: Gail Collins: So, Arthur, what did you think of Hillary Clinton’s big speech? I admit she’s never going to stun the nation with her oratory, but I thought it was pretty good.

headline_main: The Democrats Nailed It. Does It Matter?
byline_original: By Arthur C. Brooks and Gail Collins

abstract: Allies of Hillary Clinton, abandoning the standard Democratic game plan, are urging conservatives and liberals to band together against a singular threat.
snippet: Allies of Hillary Clinton, abandoning the standard Democratic game plan, are urging conservatives and liberals to band together against a singular threat.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — Democrats marked a decisive turn in their campaign against Donald J. Trump this week, moving to recast the 2016 race not as a conventional battle between left and right but as a national emergency that requires voters of all stripes to band together against a singularly menacing candidate.

headline_main: Clinton’s Portrayal of Trump as Dictator Aims at the Left and Right
headline_print_headline: Shift by Clinton Depicts Dangers in Rise of Trump

abstract: Mrs. Clinton echoed themes from the overall convention, which argued that progressive inclusiveness wasn’t incompatible with patriotism; in fact, the two go together.
snippet: Mrs. Clinton echoed themes from the overall convention, which argued that progressive inclusiveness wasn’t incompatible with patriotism; in fact, the two go together.
lead_paragraph: Toward the end of her acceptance of the Democratic presidential nomination on Thursday night, Hillary Clinton paraphrased the musical “Hamilton”: “Though we may not live to see the glory,” she said, “let us gladly join the fight.”

headline_main: Her Shot: Hillary Clinton Shares a Vision of America Out of ‘Hamilton’

abstract: Hillary Clinton and Donald J. Trump are entering the grueling homestretch of the campaign, when bickering between them could become even more biting.
snippet: Hillary Clinton and Donald J. Trump are entering the grueling homestretch of the campaign, when bickering between them could become even more biting.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — Democrats pushed on Friday to extend the excitement spurred by a four-day convention that culminated in the presidential nomination of Hillary Clinton, taking the fight against Donald J. Trump to the battleground states that could decide an election just over 100 days away.

headline_main: New York Today: A Wave of Whales

abstract: Hillary Clinton has used her nominating convention as other Democrats before her have not dared: to press for badly needed gun safety measures.
snippet: Hillary Clinton has used her nominating convention as other Democrats before her have not dared: to press for badly needed gun safety measures.
lead_paragraph: After two teenagers were shot dead and 17 people were wounded Monday in a Florida nightclub, the local police chief was quick to address a question that comes up these days whenever there’s a new gun rampage. “This was not a terrorist act,” he said. “You can put that out of your mind.”

abstract: The Republican nominee disparaged a certain “very little guy.” That seemed to be the latest in a series of barbs traded with the former New York City mayor.
snippet: The Republican nominee disparaged a certain “very little guy.” That seemed to be the latest in a series of barbs traded with the former New York City mayor.
lead_paragraph: DAVENPORT, Iowa — Nearly every time a politician has dared to offer him censure, Donald J. Trump has responded by tagging his adversary with an impish nickname. In Mr. Trump’s world, Ted Cruz became “Lyin’ Ted,” Marco Rubio was “Little Marco,” and Hillary Clinton remains “Crooked Hillary.”

headline_main: Without Naming Names, Donald Trump Steps Up Feud With Michael Bloomberg

abstract: Michael R. Bloomberg and Donald J. Trump had limited, yet friendly, interactions over the years as they occupied different circles of New York’s ultrarich. But that has changed.
snippet: Michael R. Bloomberg and Donald J. Trump had limited, yet friendly, interactions over the years as they occupied different circles of New York’s ultrarich. But that has changed.
lead_paragraph: Listening to Michael R. Bloomberg rage about Donald J. Trump in his speech at the Democratic National Convention this week — labeling him a public menace and hinting that he was not quite sane — it would be easy to think that the two billionaires had a rift going back many years.

headline_main: For Trump and Bloomberg, Cordial Ties Have Soured
headline_print_headline: Bloomberg and Trump: Cordial Ties Have Soured

abstract: Two former New York mayors, Michael R. Bloomberg and Rudolph W. Giuliani, spoke in featured spots at one of the political conventions. Their messages could not have been more different.
snippet: Two former New York mayors, Michael R. Bloomberg and Rudolph W. Giuliani, spoke in featured spots at one of the political conventions. Their messages could not have been more different.
lead_paragraph: In a few words he wrote just before going onstage on Wednesday night, Michael R. Bloomberg made a simple, arctic crack about Donald J. Trump’s mental health at the Democratic National Convention.
